                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/3057.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul at Chihuahua</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Chihuahua</hi> (<hi rend="italic">via El Paso,
                                Tex.</hi>)</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1912-03-05T11:00:00-07:04">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 5, 1912—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The warning to leave isolated points issued to Americans by Ambassador can not be
                    communicated to the hundreds of Americans in remote mining sections without
                    special messengers. I request definite instructions. Railway communications
                    closed nearly everywhere. Dictatorship exists here now. Communications closed
                    south in order to prevent apprehended advance Federals against Chihuahua.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marion Letcher.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
